[2] Brazil (Minas Gerais): cattle
Date: Thu 4 Aug 2022 13:28 BRT
Source: Globo [in Portuguese, machine trans., edited]
https://g1.globo.com/mg/sul-de-minas/noticia/2022/08/04/sobe-para-6-numero-de-casos-confirmados-de-raiva-bovina-em-muzambinho-mg.ghtml


The number of positive cases of rabies in cattle in Muzambinho (in Minas Gerais) rose to 6. The results of yet another contaminated animal was confirmed this Thursday [4 Aug 2022] by the Instituto Mineiro de Agropecuária (IMA).

According to Luzia Adão e Silva, the animal technical advisor of the regional coordination of IMA de Poços de Caldas, the animal belonged to the producer of the 1st outbreak of bovine rabies in the municipality.

The Department of Agriculture of the Municipality of Muzambinho together with the Health Surveillance confirmed on 23 Jul 2022 that 3 heads of cattle that had died in recent weeks tested positive for rabies. Last week, 2 new cases were confirmed. Also according to the prefecture, there were other suspicions reported by producers who reported some of their animals died with signs of the disease.

The city government informed that IMA is monitoring the cases and is already promoting agricultural defense actions, including a project to control vampire bats. IMA classified the situation in the city as an outbreak. The agency informed a sweep in the city would be done in search of capturing vampire bats, considered the main transmitters of the disease.

The authorities emphasize producers must vaccinate all cattle, horses, goats and sheep against rabies, with a booster after 30 days of the 1st dose and revaccinate annually. Dogs and cats over 3 months of age should also be vaccinated against rabies, which is a zoonosis transmitted between animals and humans and causes death in virtually all those infected.

The prefecture also says producers who observe neurological signs in their animals should isolate them, not have contact with saliva and seek a veterinary doctor immediately. When dealing with bats, the guideline is not to try to capture the animal and call the Health Surveillance to do so.

--
