[3] Bolivia (Pando): human, bat bite susp
Date: Tue 16 Aug 2022 16:01 BOT
Source: La Razon [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
https://www.la-razon.com/sociedad/2022/08/16/primer-caso-de-rabia-humana-en-pando-se-encuentra-en-coma-profundo/


In Pando, the 1st case of human rabies in a 53-year-old man was confirmed by the epidemiologist at the Roberto Galindo Hospital, Rick Ricardo Roca, who announced the patient has little chance of recovery and is in a deep coma.

He also informed the media the patient is an indigenous person from Barrio Puerto Alto, so they presume he was infected through the bite of a bat and intervened immediately. Likewise, as a precaution, intensive care unit and emergency unit personnel were vaccinated with an anti-rabies vaccine after contact with the infected person.

"This man arrived convulsing, with a condition that does not have the characteristics of other diseases and was assessed by specialists; due to the clinical picture and other testing, the result has been sent to the National Institute of Health Laboratories (Inlasa) of La Paz and the result came back positive," said the director of the Roberto Galindo hospital, Nahum Vásquez. He added after the complete physical examination was carried out, they did not find dog bites and, therefore, they presume it was a bite from another species, such as bats or rodents.

From the Departmental Health Service (Headquarters) of Pando, they do not rule out declaring a health alert at the regional level. Human rabies is transmitted through the bite of animals, such as dogs or bats, but doctors declare this case as "atypical" because the source of transmission in the patient has not yet been identified. [Bites of bats may not be felt by sleeping or intoxicated individuals. Bats are known to have rabies, and this would likely fit the location and the scenario. - Mod.TG]

[Byline: Judith Ochoa]

