[5] USA (South Carolina): fox, human exp
Date: Tue 2 Aug 2022 22:43 EDT
Source: The State [edited]
https://www.thestate.com/news/local/article263847267.html


Three people were exposed to a rabid fox found in Lexington County, the South Carolina Department of Health and Environmental Control (DHEC) said Tuesday [2 Aug 2022]. The fox was sent to DHEC's lab for testing on 23 Jul 2022 and was confirmed to have rabies a day later, officials said in a news release.

The animal was discovered in Lexington, in the area near Peach Tree Rock Road between Jules Road and Peachtree Rock Heritage Preserve, according to the release. The people have been told to seek medical care, health officials said. Further information on their conditions was not made available.

"If you, someone you know, or your pets have come into contact with this fox or another animal potentially having rabies, please call DHEC's Environmental Affairs, Columbia office...," health officials said in the release.

Additionally, if you think you've been exposed to a rabid animal, immediately wash the affected area with plenty of soap and water, officials said. Health officials said an exposure is direct contact -- possibly through broken skin or mucous membranes in the eyes, nose, or mouth -- from a bite, scratch, or contact with saliva, body fluids, or brain/nervous system tissue from an infected or possibly infected animal.

[Byline: Noah Feit]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[ProMED map of United States: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8705126,106

This update includes one human death and a possible pending human death. Rabies reaches almost every aspect of the world. Bats can be major contributors to this situation. While bats are important pollinators, they may also be both victim and perpetrator of spreading the virus to other animals, and to humans.

If you find yourself with a bat indoors, please report it and seek immediate medical attention. This is the time to get post-exposure prophylaxis, a measure that can save your life. Even if you do not know whether you have been bitten or scratched by a bat, but find one in your living space, seek medical assistance immediately.

Wild animals may also have rabies and interact with our pets and/or ourselves in unfortunate ways. Never take a bite to your pet or yourself lightly, especially from a wild animal. Seek medical attention for yourself and your pet immediately. One of the most important things you can do is to keep your pet current on rabies prevention vaccinations. This can save your pet's life.

This report also includes information regarding cattle with rabies. It is possible in South America it was caused by a vampire bat. The bats tend to like feeding on cattle at night. But it highlights the necessity, regardless of your location, of prevention vaccines for your livestock. Rabies is no respecter of animal size or breed, or even a person. The bats are after a blood meal and any source will do. You can and should vaccinate your livestock against rabies.

While this report does not include horses or other livestock, they are susceptible to the virus. These large animals can be devastating to us if they are rabid. A vaccine can protect your animal investment as well as your own life.

If you are bitten, wash the wound, and seek medical attention immediately. Post-exposure prophylaxis is a series of injections given in the muscle of the arm. However, time between being bitten and seeking treatment is a narrow window, so please seek medical assistance quickly. - Mod.TG]
